Author: William Hendricks (hendrickswi)
Date: 04/27/2026
Sprint 5
File(s) being reviewed: FlyingEnemy.cs, AxisEnemy.cs, SpawnerEnemy.cs
Author of file(s): Ethan Chitturi (CoolestToDoIt)

Comments: As I mentioned in my last code review, the enemy behavior (strategy pattern) 
design is super modular and reusable! I also think the usage of our ITargetProvider and 
IPathfindingService interfaces to implement pathfinding for enemies is great! And, the
usage of enemy configs to help separate hardcoded stats from the enemy type
classes is also great!

However, I believe there are few things that could be improved:

  1) Anti-pattern in FlyingEnemy.cs and AxisEnemy.cs: string comparisons to determine enemy
behaviors. This is highly unmaintainable if the project grows in size. You have to edit these
classes everytime you want to add/remove an enemy.

  2) Tight coupling in SpawnerEnemy.cs: In the method SpawnerEnemy.RegisterAttack(), you are
hard-coding that any SpawnerEnemy should spawn a SpiderEnemy. This is also highly unmaintainable.
You have to change this anytime you want to add/remove an enemy.

Suggested Changes:

  1) Add respective variables to the config object you use in all of the classes.
Something like a FleesFromPlayer boolean and a PatrolAxis enum.

  2) Use some sort of factory?
